<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Cameron, Duncan. A sketch of the Customs, Manners, and Way of Living of the Natives, All the Quadrupeds, as Well as Birds, and Fishes, that are Found in the barren Country About Nipigon, <span class="AddHand-editors">[1804]</span>. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0026</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">ago, that killed her husband for fear of herself and children being eaten by him &#8211; her suspicion came by seeing him <span class="AddHand-author">drink</span> a large quantity of raw blood<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> quite warm, out of the animal&#8217;s body that had just been killed and opened; that he appeared, as she said, quite wild and distracted in his looks, which frightened her so much, that she immediately split his head in two with an axe before he had time to become invulnerable &#8211; she said likewise, that he told her several times that he dreamed that he would become a Man Eater; and, said she, it was high time to kill him; although his body was quite warm when I opened him, his heart was already full of Ice within him &#8211; and indeed she was highly approved for what she did, even by his nighest relatives.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">There is no instance of a Single, or widow woman havings any Bastards &#8211; but there is at the same time no doubt but that they would be numerous,</p>

